\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What happens to the returns to factors when the price of goods changes?
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Pg.
 15 in Feenstra and Hanson
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We got a preview of the answer to this question in our study of the FF and
 SS curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We'll add to these results by looking at real returns
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stolper-Samuelson Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 2
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stolper-Samuelson
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A rise in the relative price of a good will lead to a rise in the return
 to the factor used most intensively in the production of that good.
 There will also be a fall in the return to the other factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the price of textiles increases, the model predicts that wage increases
 whereas the return to capital decreases
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Wages increases because labour is the input used most intensively in textiles
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
What about 
\emph on
real
\emph default
 returns?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What we care about is the purchasing power of our workers
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Which means we must look at real returns: 
\begin_inset Formula $w/p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r/p$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note, when a person buys both computers and textiles, her real return is
 wages 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 normalized by a price index 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $w/\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P}$
\end_inset

 is a function of the price of both textiles and computers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Real returns to capital
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose the price of textiles rises while the price of computers stays the
 same
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We demonstrated that 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 rises and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 falls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{T}$
\end_inset

 increased and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{C}$
\end_inset

 did not change, 
\begin_inset Formula $r/P_{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r/P_{T}$
\end_inset

 both decrease
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, the overall real return to capital falls
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Real returns to labour
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Since the price of computer did not change, 
\begin_inset Formula $w/P_{C}$
\end_inset

 increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But it is not clear if 
\begin_inset Formula $w/P_{T}$
\end_inset

 increased since both 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{T}$
\end_inset

 increased
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From the FF-SS Curves, a rise in 
\begin_inset Formula $w/r$
\end_inset

 results in a rise of 
\begin_inset Formula $K/L$
\end_inset

 in both industries
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This can be interpreted as firms substituting towards the more inexpensive
 factor, capital
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Real returns to labour
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
includegraphics[scale=.125]{"figures/l3/ffss 2"}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Real returns to labour
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $K/L$
\end_inset

 raises the marginal product of labour
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Each worker is working with more capital, so their individual output increases
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
From perfect competition, 
\begin_inset Formula $w/P_{T}=MPL_{T}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $MPL_{T}=\frac{\partial F_{T}(K,L)}{\partial L}$
\end_inset

, marginal product of labour
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{T}(K,L)=K^{1/3}L^{2/3}\implies MPL_{T}=\frac{2}{3}\left(\frac{K}{L}\right)^{1/3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The increase in the marginal product of labour increases 
\begin_inset Formula $w/P_{T}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Argument applies to returns to capital
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Each unit of capital is now working with less labour, thus the marginal
 product of capital falls which means the purchasing power of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 in terms of both goods fall
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $r/P_{T}=MPK_{T}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rybczynski
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset ERT
