\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What happens to structure of production when the distribution of factor
 endowments changes?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Changes in stock of capital and labour: 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{L}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Can also give insight on how factor endowments determine a country's industrial
 composition
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Dutch Disease
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Commodity booms (such as the discovery of oil) tend to cause industrial
 restructuring, most of the time the type that is harmful to the long-term
 development of the country
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Economist coined the term in 1977 to describe the woes of the Dutch
 economy.
 Large gas reserves had been discovered in 1959.
 Dutch exports soared.
 But, we noticed, there was a contrast between "external health and internal
 ailments".
 From 1970 to 1977 unemployment increased from 1.1% to 5.1%.
 Corporate investment was tumbling.
 We explained the puzzle by pointing to the high value of the guilder, then
 the Dutch currency.
 Gas exports had led to an influx of foreign currency, which increased demand
 for the guilder and thus made it stronger.
 That made other parts of the economy less competitive in international
 markets.
 That was not the only problem.
 Gas extraction was (and is) a relatively capital-intensive business, which
 generated few jobs.
 And in an attempt to stop the guilder from appreciating too fast, the Dutch
 kept interest rates low.
 That prompted investment to rush out of the country, crimping future economic
 potential.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://www.economist.com/blogs/economist-explains/2014/11/economist-explains-2
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Given a set of goods prices, the SS curve give the corresponding relative
 factor price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given this relative factor price, the FF curves gives us the capital-labour
 ratio in each sector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Along with the resource constraint, we can use this information to solve
 for factor allocation within this country
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These factor allocations are 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{C}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{C}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{T}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let's go back to the numerical example from Lecture 2b
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q_{C}=K_{C}^{2/3}L_{C}^{1/3} &  & Q_{T}=K_{T}^{1/3}L_{T}^{2/3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These production functions implied the following FF curves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\frac{w}{r}=2\frac{K_{T}}{L_{T}} &  & \frac{w}{r}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{K_{C}}{L_{C}}\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\frac{w}{r}=2\frac{K_{T}}{L_{T}} &  & \frac{w}{r}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{K_{C}}{L_{C}}\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now suppose relative prices are such that the SS curves gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{w}{r}=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
2K_{T} & = & L_{T}\label{eq:1}\\
K_{C} & = & 2L_{C}\label{eq:2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In optimum, all resources in a country will be employed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This gives us the following equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
K_{T}+K_{C} & = & \bar{K}\\
L_{T}+L_{C} & = & \bar{L}\label{eq:4}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 with no subscripts are the stock of capital and labour
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:4"

\end_inset

 gives us four equations and four unknowns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, we can solve for optimal capital and labour in each industry: 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{T}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{T}^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that the solutions will be a function of the parameters of the optimization
 problem
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{T}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{C}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{T}^{*}$
\end_inset

 will change as the stock of capital 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{K}$
\end_inset

 and labour 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{L}$
\end_inset

 changes
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Edgeworth Box
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let's see how this can be done using the Edgeworth Box
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Allows us to visualize how changes in endowment affect input use in each
 industry and, subsequently, their level of output
\end_layout

