\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $K_{T}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{T}$
\end_inset

 increases 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies Q_{T}$
\end_inset

 increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $K_{C}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{C}$
\end_inset

 falls 
\begin_inset Formula $\implies Q_{C}$
\end_inset

 falls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These results summarizes the prediction made by the Rybczynski theorem
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 2
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
An increase in a factor endowment will increase the output of the industry
 using it intensively, and a decrease in the output of the other industry
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 2
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
An increase in a factor endowment will increase the output of the industry
 using it intensively, and a decrease in the output of the other industry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Labour is used more intensively in textiles than in computers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore, an increase in the stock of labour increased output in textiles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
and decreased output in computers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 2
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rybczynski Theorem
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
An increase in a factor endowment will increase the output of the industry
 using it intensively, and a decrease in the output of the other industry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An alternative interpretation is that countries will produce more of the
 good that intensively uses its more abundant factor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
E.g.
 Mexico will produce more textiles than computers relative to Canada because:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
it has relatively more labour than capital compared with Canada
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
textiles is more labour intensive than computers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This can be shown in each countries relative supply curve
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Relative Supply Curve
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
includegraphics[scale=.10]{"figures/l3/rsrd 1a"}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Relative Supply Curve
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For a given relative goods price, South---the labour abundant country----produce
s more textiles relative to computers than North---the capital abundant
 country
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What underlie the difference in these two supply curve is the fact that
 we have assumed that goods and factor prices remain constant when we changed
 the labour stock in the Edgeworth Box
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This is why the slopes of the Output Expansion Paths did not change as the
 stock of labour endowments increased
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Relative Supply Curve
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So for each 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{T}/P_{C}$
\end_inset

, the difference in 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{T}/Q_{C}$
\end_inset

 in the relative supply curves between the two countries are just the result
 of changes in labour endowment as seen in the Edgeworth Box
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can also derive these relative supply curves using PPFs
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Rybczynski and PPF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
PPFs in the HO Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Unlike the Ricardian Model, the PPF in the HO model are bowed out
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is because of the diminishing marginal returns assumption we made on
 the production function, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{j}=F_{j}(K,L)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Increasing the production of good 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 entails increasing usage of both capital and labour
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But as we use more and more of these inputs, the marginal output we get
 is decreasing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This results in a bowed out PPF curve
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
PPFs in the HO Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
includegraphics[scale=.08]{"figures/l3/ppf 1"}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Isovalue Line
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Optimum output can be attained by maximizing the value of output
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V & = & P_{C}Q_{C}+P_{T}Q_{T}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rewrite this as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{T}=\frac{V}{P_{T}}-\frac{P_{C}}{P_{T}}Q_{C}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This gives us all the combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{C}$
\end_inset

 that attains the value of output 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Call this line the 
\series bold
isovalue line
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This is not the same as the 
\series bold
isovalue curve
\series default
 in the Lerner Diagram
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

